                                                                                                                                                                                         
⏺ Here's a breakdown of the key differences explaining the performance gap:                                                                                                               
                                                                                                                                                                                          
  1. Staggering difference in workload                                                                                                                                                    
                                                                                                                                                                                          
  ┌─────────────┬──────────────────┬────────────────┬────────────────┐                                                                                                                    
  │  Parameter  │ beatmapper (C++) │ v0.3.html (JS) │     Ratio      │                                                                                                                    
  ├─────────────┼──────────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────┤                                                                                                                    
  │ FFT size    │ 2048             │ 8192           │ 4× bigger      │
  ├─────────────┼──────────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────┤                                                                                                                    
  │ Hop size    │ 512              │ 128            │ 4× more frames │                                                                                                                    
  ├─────────────┼──────────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────┤                                                                                                                    
  │ Channels    │ mono             │ stereo         │ 2×             │                                                                                                                    
  ├─────────────┼──────────────────┼────────────────┼────────────────┤
  │ Columns cap │ 8192             │ 50000          │ 6× more        │
  └─────────────┴──────────────────┴────────────────┴────────────────┘

  For a 3-minute song at 44100 Hz:
  - C++: ~15,500 frames → capped to 8,192 FFTs of size 2048
  - JS: ~62,000 frames, stereo → ~124,000 FFTs of size 8192

  That's roughly 60–70× more total FFT work before accounting for language speed.

  2. Language speed

  The C++ FFT runs as compiled native code on the CPU — even without precomputed twiddles (it recomputes cosf/sinf per stage). The JS version runs in a Worker — still
  interpreted/JIT-compiled JavaScript. For tight inner loops like FFT butterfly stages, native C is easily 10–50× faster per operation.

  Combined with the 60–70× more work: the total wall-clock difference is in the range of 600–3000×.

  3. Rendering architecture

  beatmapper: Computes once, uploads a single RGBA GPU texture, renders it in one dl->AddImage() call. GPU hardware handles all bilinear interpolation. Zero per-frame CPU work.

  v0.3.html: On every animation frame, drawSpectrogram() runs a full nested w × h pixel loop in JS, calling sampleSpec() (bilinear interpolation in JS) for each pixel. So the canvas is
  slow to paint even after the FFT is done.

  4. Async yield overhead

  The JS worker does await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 0)) every 64 frames to keep the page responsive. Each setTimeout round-trip is ~4ms minimum, so for 62,000 frames that's ~3,800
  yields → adds ~15 seconds of forced idle time on top of compute time.

  What would help

  In rough order of impact:
  1. Increase hop size (e.g. 512 or 1024) — reduces frame count 4–8×, biggest win
  2. Decrease FFT size to match beatmapper's 2048 — less frequency resolution but 4× faster per FFT
  3. Move rendering to a pre-built ImageData / OffscreenCanvas — compute once, blit on draw instead of per-pixel JS loop each frame
  4. Reduce setTimeout yield frequency — every 512 or 1024 frames instead of 64
  5. Use the PFFFT wasm engine for FFTs — likely 2–5× faster than the JS engine at equivalent sizes

  The beatmapper's "almost instant" feel comes down to: 70× less data × 10–50× faster language × zero per-frame rendering cost.

